Introduction:

# With plethora prediction models available, it is never easy to decide which model to use. Model selection itself could be a skill and can be honed by practice with different data and variation in functionalities. 
# The primary goal of this assignment is to predict the 'sales' of Video games based on different platform. Depending on this analysis, we can decide how would the future versions of a particular a game perform in terms of sale/grossing.  

# Target variable: NA_Sales

# Note that our target is Numerical in nature and hence we will use various regression techniques to build a model that will help predict sales of games.

As we know, R-squared is a goodness-of-fit measure for linear regression models. This statistic indicates the percentage of the variance in the dependent variable that the independent variables explain collectively. R-squared in our case is not extremely bad but could be lot better.

We can also observe that the significance level(p-value) for many variables and their specific levels are significant. For eg:

PS3, PS4 and PSP variables have little to no significance on the sales output. However, PS2 has very high significance. From this, we can deduce that if a game has done well on Playstation 2(PS2), it will certainly do well on other future versions i.e. PS4, PSP.

1.D Creating data partition to perform modelling:

NA_sales_Train <- NA_sales_filtered[inTrain,] #Training set
NA_sales_Test <- NA_sales_filtered[-inTrain,] #Testing set

3.A Corss validation: This is a technique used in model selection to better estimate the test error of a predictive model. The idea behind cross-validation is to create a number of partitions of sample observations, known as the validation sets/folds, from the training data set.

We can achieve Cross validation using ‘loop’ commands or ‘lapply’ and functions.

Now, we create a cross-validation Function – ‘cv_function’. We do this so that we can reuse the function depending on our preference of Model and no. of folds.

# Creating a cv_function with input arguments that could be altered for re-use.

cv_function <- function(df, target, nFolds, seedVal, prediction_method, metrics_list)
{
  # create folds
  set.seed(seedVal)
  folds = createFolds(df[,target],nFolds) 
  # perform cross validation
  cv_results <- lapply(folds, function(x)
  { 
    test_target <- df[x,target]
    test_input  <- df[x,-target]

    train_target <- df[-x,target]
    train_input <- df[-x,-target]

    prediction_model <- prediction_method(train_target~.,train_input) 
    pred<- predict(prediction_model,test_input)
    return(mmetric(test_target,pred,metrics_list))
  })
  # generate means and sds and show cv results, means and sds using kable
  cv_results_m <- as.matrix(as.data.frame(cv_results))
  cv_mean<- as.matrix(rowMeans(cv_results_m))
  cv_sd <- as.matrix(rowSds(cv_results_m))
  colnames(cv_mean) <- "Mean"
  colnames(cv_sd) <- "Sd"
  cv_all <- cbind(cv_results_m, cv_mean, cv_sd)
  kable(t(cv_all),digits=2)
}

Now that we have our cross vaidation function defined, we can apply it on different regression models across no. of folds.

Hence, we use our cv_function to evaluate ‘linear’, ‘rpart’ and ‘M5P’ models by 5-fold cross-validation.

Conclusion: Regression models need tuning to account for non-linearity. Hence, we demonstrate this accomodation through cross-validation technique and tranformations.

Of all the models, Model-tree has performed the best as per evaluation metrics.

Cross validation certainly provides much better insight into data.

Quadratic and Logarithmic transformations further improves the model preformance by nearly similar degree.
